In early Latin, qui is a common instrumenta} (or perhaps locative) form of the relative, interrogative, or indefinite pronoun. Hence a variety of uses. Here, qni z quo. The imperfect tense is used in aleret, probably because esse relicui is the same as esse relictum, which would allow second-ary sequence, but in colloquial Latin there is much frecdom in the sequence of tenses—relicui: partitive genitive, with nil. The word has four syllables in the older literature, being later reliquus.
